<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Endemic to Bolivia, where it grows in cerrado on sandy soil in two areas of Santa Cruz Department.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">BOLIVIA. Santa Cruz</emphasis>
: Chiquitos, around Santiago de Chiquitos 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
R. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Guillén">Guillen</normalizedToken>
et al.
</emphasis>
4799 (MO, USZ); 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">J.R.I. Wood et al.</emphasis>
20171 (BOLV, K, LPB, USZ); south of Taperas 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">J.R.I. Wood et al.</emphasis>
23578 (K, LPB, UB, USZ); south of San 
<normalizedToken originalValue="José">Jose</normalizedToken>
de Chiquitos, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">J.R.I. Wood et al.</emphasis>
29159 (LPB, USZ).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Griseb." authorityName="Griseb." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nitida">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea nitida</emphasis>
Griseb.
</taxonomicName>
, particularly 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="nitida" subSpecies="krapovickasii">
subsp. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">krapovickasii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the leaves are glabrous or obscurely pubescent, their base cordate to truncate, rather than truncate to cuneate, the petioles very short (0.3-0.9 cm, not 2-4 cm), the cymes usually 1-3-flowered (not up to 7-flowered) and the sepals green, pubescent, rather than grey-tomentellous, 11-12 mm (not 7-9 mm) long. Molecular data suggest the two species are not closely related.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
